# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wolfram-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] A **computer algebra system** (**CAS**) or **symbolic algebra system** (**SAS**) is any mathematical software with the ability to manipulate mathematical expressions in a way similar to the traditional manual computations of mathematicians and scientists.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] The development of the computer algebra systems in the second half of the 20th century is part of the discipline of "computer algebra" or "symbolic computation", which has spurred work in algorithms over mathematical objects such as polynomials.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Computer algebra systems may be divided into two classes: specialized and general-purpose.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] The specialized ones are devoted to a specific part of mathematics, such as number theory, group theory, or teaching of elementary mathematics.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] General-purpose computer algebra systems aim to be useful to a user working in any scientific field that requires manipulation of mathematical expressions.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] The library must not only provide for the needs of the users, but also the needs of the simplifier.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] For example, the computation of polynomial greatest common divisors is systematically used for the simplification of expressions involving fractions.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] This large amount of required computer capabilities explains the small number of general-purpose computer algebra systems.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Significant systems include Axiom, GAP, Maxima, Magma, Maple, Mathematica, SageMath, and SymPy.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] In the 1950s, while computers were mainly used for numerical computations, there were some research projects into using them for symbolic manipulation.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Computer algebra systems began to appear in the 1960s and evolved out of two quite different sources—the requirements of theoretical physicists and research into artificial intelligence.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] A prime example of the first development was the pioneering work conducted by the later Nobel Prize laureate in physics Martinus Veltman, who designed a program for symbolic mathematics, especially high-energy physics, called Schoonschip (Dutch for "clean ship") in 1963.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Using Lisp as the programming basis, Carl Engelman created MATHLAB in 1964 at MITRE within an artificial-intelligence research environment.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] MATHLAB was later made available to users on PDP-6 and PDP-10 systems running TOPS-10 or TENEX in universities.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Today it can still be used on SIMH emulations of the PDP-10.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] MATHLAB ("**math**ematical **lab**oratory") should not be confused with MATLAB ("**mat**rix **lab**oratory"), which is a system for numerical computation built 15 years later at the University of New Mexico.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] In 1987, Hewlett-Packard introduced the first hand-held calculator CAS with the HP-28 series.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Other early handheld calculators with symbolic algebra capabilities included the Texas Instruments TI-89 series and TI-92 calculator, and the Casio CFX-9970G.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] The first popular computer algebra systems were muMATH, Reduce, Derive (based on muMATH), and Macsyma; a copyleft version of Macsyma is called Maxima.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Commercial systems include Mathematica and Maple, which are commonly used by research mathematicians, scientists, and engineers.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Freely available alternatives include SageMath (which can act as a front-end to several other free and nonfree CAS).
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Other significant systems include Axiom, GAP, Maxima and Magma.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] The movement to web-based applications in the early 2000s saw the release of WolframAlpha, an online search engine and CAS which includes the capabilities of Mathematica.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] More recently, computer algebra systems have been implemented using artificial neural networks.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] In the above, the word *some* indicates that the operation cannot always be performed.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Some computer algebra systems focus on specialized disciplines; these are typically developed in academia and are free.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] They can be inefficient for numeric operations as compared to numeric systems.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Numeric domains supported typically include floating-point representation of real numbers, integers (of unbounded size), complex (floating-point representation), interval representation of reals, rational number (exact representation) and algebraic numbers.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] There have been many advocates for increasing the use of computer algebra systems in primary and secondary-school classrooms.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] The primary reason for such advocacy is that computer algebra systems represent real-world math more than do paper-and-pencil or hand calculator based mathematics.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] This push for increasing computer usage in mathematics classrooms has been supported by some boards of education.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] It has even been mandated in the curriculum of some regions.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Computer algebra systems have been extensively used in higher education.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] Many universities offer either specific courses on developing their use, or they implicitly expect students to use them for their course work.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] The companies that develop computer algebra systems have pushed to increase their prevalence among university and college programs.
[src:wolfram-language/computer-algebra-system] CAS-equipped calculators are not permitted on the ACT, the PLAN, the SAT, and in some classrooms though it may be permitted on College Board's calculator-permitted AP tests, including the AP Calculus, Chemistry, Physics, and Statistics exams.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] In mathematics and computer science, **computer algebra**, also called **symbolic computation** or **algebraic computation**, is a scientific area that refers to the study and development of algorithms and software for manipulating mathematical expressions and other mathematical objects.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Computer algebra is widely used to experiment in mathematics and to design the formulas that are used in numerical programs.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] It is also used for complete scientific computations, when purely numerical methods fail, as in public key cryptography, or for some non-linear problems.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Some authors distinguish *computer algebra* from *symbolic computation*, using the latter name to refer to kinds of symbolic computation other than the computation with mathematical formulas.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Some authors use *symbolic computation* for the computer-science aspect of the subject and *computer algebra* for the mathematical aspect.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] In some languages, the name of the field is not a direct translation of its English name.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Typically, it is called *calcul formel* in French, which means "formal computation".
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This name reflects the ties this field has with formal methods.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] There is no learned society that is specific to computer algebra, but this function is assumed by the special interest group of the Association for Computing Machinery named SIGSAM (Special Interest Group on Symbolic and Algebraic Manipulation).
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] There are several annual conferences on computer algebra, the premier being ISSAC (International Symposium on Symbolic and Algebraic Computation), which is regularly sponsored by SIGSAM.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] There are several journals specializing in computer algebra, the top one being *Journal of Symbolic Computation* founded in 1985 by Bruno Buchberger.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] There are also several other journals that regularly publish articles in computer algebra.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] As numerical software is highly efficient for approximate numerical computation, it is common, in computer algebra, to emphasize *exact* computation with exactly represented data.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Such an exact representation implies that, even when the size of the output is small, the intermediate data generated during a computation may grow in an unpredictable way.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This behavior is called *expression swell*.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] To alleviate this problem, various methods are used in the representation of the data, as well as in the algorithms that manipulate them.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] The usual number systems used in numerical computation are floating point numbers and integers of a fixed, bounded size.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Neither of these is convenient for computer algebra, due to expression swell.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Therefore, the basic numbers used in computer algebra are the integers of the mathematicians, commonly represented by an unbounded signed sequence of digits in some base of numeration, usually the largest base allowed by the machine word.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] These integers allow one to define the rational numbers, which are irreducible fractions of two integers.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Programming an efficient implementation of the arithmetic operations is a hard task.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Therefore, most free computer algebra systems, and some commercial ones such as Mathematica and Maple, use the GMP library, which is thus a *de facto* standard.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Except for numbers and variables, every mathematical expression may be viewed as the symbol of an operator followed by a sequence of operands.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] In computer-algebra software, the expressions are usually represented in this way.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This representation is very flexible, and many things that seem not to be mathematical expressions at first glance, may be represented and manipulated as such.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] For example, an equation may be considered as an expression with "=" as its leading operator, and a matrix may be represented as an expression with "matrix" as an operator and its rows as operands.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Even programs may be considered and represented as expressions with operator "procedure" and, at least, two operands, the list of parameters and the body, which is itself an expression with "body" as an operator and a sequence of instructions as operands.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Conversely, any mathematical expression may be viewed as a program.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] For example, the expression *a* + *b* may be viewed as a program for the addition, with *a* and *b* as parameters.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Executing this program consists of *evaluating* the expression for given values of *a* and *b*; if they are not given any values, then the result of the evaluation is simply its input.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This process of delayed evaluation is fundamental in computer algebra.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] As the size of the operands of an expression is unpredictable and may change during a working session, the sequence of the operands is usually represented as a sequence of either pointers (like in Macsyma) or entries in a hash table (like in Maple).
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] A simpler expression than this is generally desired, and simplification is needed when working with general expressions.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This simplification is normally done through rewriting rules.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] There are several classes of rewriting rules to be considered.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] The simplest are rules that always reduce the size of the expression, like *E* − *E* → 0 or sin(0) → 0.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] They are systematically applied in computer algebra systems.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] A difficulty occurs with associative operations like addition and multiplication.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] The standard way to deal with associativity is to consider that addition and multiplication have an arbitrary number of operands; that is, that *a* + *b* + *c* is represented as "+"(*a*, *b*, *c*).
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] In other words, in the internal representation of the expressions, there is no subtraction nor division nor unary minus, outside the representation of the numbers.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Another difficulty occurs with the commutativity of addition and multiplication.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] The problem is to quickly recognize the like terms in order to combine or cancel them.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Testing every pair of terms is costly with very long sums and products.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] To address this, Macsyma sorts the operands of sums and products into an order that places like terms in consecutive places, allowing easy detection.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] In Maple, a hash function is designed for generating collisions when like terms are entered, allowing them to be combined as soon as they are introduced.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This allows subexpressions that appear several times in a computation to be immediately recognized and stored only once.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This saves memory and speeds up computation by avoiding repetition of the same operations on identical expressions.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Some rewriting rules sometimes increase and sometimes decrease the size of the expressions to which they are applied.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This is the case for the distributive law or trigonometric identities.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] For the distributive law, the computer function that applies this rewriting rule is typically called "expand".
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] The reverse rewriting rule, called "factor", requires a non-trivial algorithm, which is thus a key function in computer algebra systems (see Polynomial factorization).
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Some fundamental mathematical questions arise when one wants to manipulate mathematical expressions in a computer.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] We consider mainly the case of the multivariate rational fractions.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This is not a real restriction, because, as soon as the irrational functions appearing in an expression are simplified, they are usually considered as new indeterminates.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] There are two notions of equality for mathematical expressions.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] *Syntactic equality* is the equality of their representation in a computer.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] It is known from Richardson's theorem that there may not exist an algorithm that decides whether two expressions representing numbers are semantically equal if exponentials and logarithms are allowed in the expressions.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Accordingly, (semantic) equality may be tested only on some classes of expressions such as the polynomials and rational fractions.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] To test the equality of two expressions, instead of designing specific algorithms, it is usual to put expressions in some *canonical form* or to put their difference in a *normal form*, and to test the syntactic equality of the result.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] In computer algebra, "canonical form" and "normal form" are not synonymous.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] A *canonical form* is such that two expressions in canonical form are semantically equal if and only if they are syntactically equal, while a *normal form* is such that an expression in normal form is semantically zero only if it is syntactically zero.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] In other words, zero has a unique representation as an expression in normal form.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Normal forms are usually preferred in computer algebra for several reasons.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Firstly, canonical forms may be more costly to compute than normal forms.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] For example, to put a polynomial in canonical form, one has to expand every product through the distributive law, while it is not necessary with a normal form (see below).
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Secondly, it may be the case, like for expressions involving radicals, that a canonical form, if it exists, depends on some arbitrary choices and that these choices may be different for two expressions that have been computed independently.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] This may make the use of a canonical form impractical.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Early computer algebra systems, such as the ENIAC at the University of Pennsylvania, relied on human computers or programmers to reprogram it between calculations, manipulate its many physical modules (or panels), and feed its IBM card reader.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Female mathematicians handled the majority of ENIAC programming human-guided computation: Jean Jennings, Marlyn Wescoff, Ruth Lichterman, Betty Snyder, Frances Bilas, and Kay McNulty led said efforts.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] In 1960, John McCarthy explored an extension of primitive recursive functions for computing symbolic expressions through the Lisp programming language while at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Early efforts at symbolic computation, in the 1960s and 1970s, faced challenges surrounding the inefficiency of long-known algorithms when ported to computer algebra systems.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Predecessors to Project MAC, such as ALTRAN, sought to overcome algorithmic limitations through advancements in hardware and interpreters, while later efforts turned towards software optimization.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] A large part of the work of researchers in the field consisted of revisiting classical algebra to increase its effectiveness while developing efficient algorithms for use in computer algebra.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] An example of this type of work is the computation of polynomial greatest common divisors, a task required to simplify fractions and an essential component of computer algebra.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Classical algorithms for this computation, such as Euclid's algorithm, proved inefficient over infinite fields; algorithms from linear algebra faced similar struggles.
[src:wolfram-language/symbolic-computation] Thus, researchers turned to discovering methods of reducing polynomials (such as those over a ring of integers or a unique factorization domain) to a variant efficiently computable via a Euclidean algorithm.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The **Wolfram Language** (/ˈwʊlfrəm/ *WUUL-frəm*) is a proprietary, high-level multi-paradigm programming language developed by Wolfram Research.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] It emphasizes symbolic computation, functional programming, and rule-based programming and can employ arbitrary structures and data.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] It is the programming language of the mathematical symbolic computation program Mathematica.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The Wolfram Language was part of the initial version of Mathematica in 1988.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] Symbolic aspects of the engine make it a computer algebra system.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The language can perform integration, differentiation, matrix manipulations, and solve differential equations using a set of rules.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] Also, the initial version introduced the notebook model and the ability to embed sound and images, according to Theodore Gray's patent.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] Wolfram also added features for more complex tasks, such as 3D modeling.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] A name was finally adopted for the language in 2013, as Wolfram Research decided to make a version of the language engine free for Raspberry Pi users, and they needed to come up with a name for it.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] It was included in the recommended software bundle that the Raspberry Pi Foundation provides for beginners, which caused some controversy due to the Wolfram language's proprietary nature.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] Plans to port the Wolfram language to the Intel Edison were announced after the board's introduction at CES 2014 but were never released.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] In 2019, a link was added to make Wolfram libraries compatible with the Unity game engine, giving game developers access to the language's high-level functions.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The Wolfram Language syntax is overall similar to the M-expression of 1960s LISP, with support for infix operators and "function-notation" function calls.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The Wolfram language writes basic arithmetic expressions using infix operators.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The `:=` is a "SetDelayed operator", so that the x is not immediately looked for.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] `x_` is syntax sugar for `Pattern[x, Blank[]]`, i.e. a "blank" for any value to replace x in the rest of the evaluation.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The `/;` operator is "condition", so that the rule only applies when `y>z`.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The three underscores are a syntax for a `BlankNullSequence[]`, for a sequence that can be null.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The pattern matching system also easily gives rise to rule-based integration and derivation.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The official and reference implementation of the Wolfram Language lies in Mathematica and associated online services.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] Wolfram Research has, however, released a parser of the language under the open source MIT License.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The parser was originally developed in C++ but was rewritten in Rust in 2023.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] In the over three-decade-long existence of the Wolfram language, a number of open-source third-party implementations have also been developed.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] Richard Fateman's MockMMA from 1991 is of historical note, both for being the earliest reimplementation and for having received a cease-and-desist from Wolfram.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] Modern ones still being maintained as of April 2020 include Symja in Java, expreduce in Golang, and SymPy-based Mathics.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] These implementations focus on the core language and the computer algebra system that it implies, not on the online "knowledgebase" features of Wolfram.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] In 2019, Wolfram Research released the freeware Wolfram Engine, to be used as a programming library in non-commercial software.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] This developer-only engine provides a command-line shell of the Mathematica evaluator (with a limited number of kernels) and requires signup and license activation over the web.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The freely available Jupyter Notebook/Lab project provides a protocol (ZMQ) to connect their notebooks to various languages, this is available as an alternative to the text-only CLI interface via the Wolfram Kernel for Jupyter.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-language] The language was officially named in June 2013 and has been used as the backend of Mathematica and other Wolfram technologies for over 30 years.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Mathematica is split into two parts: the kernel and the front end.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] The kernel interprets expressions (Wolfram Language code) and returns result expressions, which can then be displayed by the front end.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] The original front end, designed by Theodore Gray in 1988, consists of a notebook interface and allows the creation and editing of notebook documents that can contain code, plaintext, images, and graphics.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Code development is also supported through support in a range of standard integrated development environment (IDE) including Eclipse, IntelliJ IDEA, Atom, Vim, Visual Studio Code and Git.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] The Mathematica Kernel also includes a command line front end.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Other interfaces include JMath, based on GNU Readline and WolframScript which runs self-contained Mathematica programs (with arguments) from the UNIX command line.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Capabilities for high-performance computing were extended with the introduction of packed arrays in version 4 (1999) and sparse matrices (version 5, 2003), and by adopting the GNU Multiple Precision Arithmetic Library to evaluate high-precision arithmetic.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Version 5.2 (2005) added automatic multi-threading when computations are performed on multi-core computers.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] This release included CPU-specific optimized libraries.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] In addition Mathematica is supported by third party specialist acceleration hardware such as ClearSpeed.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Support for CUDA and OpenCL GPU hardware was added in 2010.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] As of Version 14, there are 6,602 built-in functions and symbols in the Wolfram Language.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Stephen Wolfram announced the launch of the Wolfram Function Repository in June 2019 as a way for the public Wolfram community to contribute functionality to the Wolfram Language.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] There are currently more than 3000 functions contributed as Resource Functions.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] In addition to the Wolfram Function Repository, there is a Wolfram Data Repository with computable data and the Wolfram Neural Net Repository for machine learning.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Wolfram Mathematica is the basis of the Combinatorica package, which adds discrete mathematics functionality in combinatorics and graph theory to the program.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Communication with other applications can be done using a protocol called Wolfram Symbolic Transfer Protocol (WSTP).
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] It allows communication between the Wolfram Mathematica kernel and the front end and provides a general interface between the kernel and other applications.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Wolfram Research freely distributes a developer kit for linking applications written in the programming language C to the Mathematica kernel through WSTP using J/Link., a Java program that can ask Mathematica to perform computations.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Similar functionality is achieved with .NET /Link, but with .NET programs instead of Java programs.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Other languages that connect to Mathematica include Haskell, AppleScript, Racket, Visual Basic, Python, and Clojure.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Mathematica supports the generation and execution of Modelica models for systems modeling and connects with Wolfram System Modeler.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Links are also available to many third-party software packages and APIs.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Mathematica can also capture real-time data from a variety of sources and can read and write to public blockchains (Bitcoin, Ethereum, and ARK).
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] It supports import and export of over 220 data, image, video, sound, computer-aided design (CAD), geographic information systems (GIS), document, and biomedical formats.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] In 2019, support was added for compiling Wolfram Language code to LLVM.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Version 12.3 of the Wolfram Language added support for Arduino.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Mathematica is also integrated with Wolfram Alpha, an online answer engine that provides additional data, some of which is kept updated in real time, for users who use Mathematica with an internet connection.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Some of the data sets include astronomical, chemical, geopolitical, language, biomedical, airplane, and weather data, in addition to mathematical data (such as knots and polyhedra).
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Mathematica has been criticized for being closed source.
[src:wolfram-language/wolfram-mathematica] Wolfram Research claims keeping Mathematica closed source is central to its business model and the continuity of the software.
